Nicolas Maduro has increasingly relied on crackdowns and gerrymandering to secure his rule over Venezuela. The economic situation is becoming more dire, protests are escalating, and there is growing opposition towards the Maduro government. The Maduro regime has also responded with crackdowns on protesters and has vetoed any legislation passed by the opposition. The only real threats to Maduro's regime are the opposition and the military. The opposition, however, has been very disorganized due to ideological and political differences and have failed to create a united front against Maduro. Military coups have worked to create democracies before, as seen in Romania near the end of the Cold War. However, Maduro has recognized the threat from the military and has been promoted loyal officers and shared the oil wealth with the military, ensuring their loyalty. However, lower ranking officials and foot soldiers have joined the protesters as they have been largely ostracized from the military. If this, continues there could be a good chance for a coup in Venezuela and Maduro's replacement.

It is extremely unlikely that Maduro will cease to be president by July 1, 2018. An early presidential election is set for May 20, and with major opposition politicians banned from running, Maduro is widely expected to win reelection and stay in office. Controlling the nation's judiciary branch, Maduro is effectively impossible to be removed constitutionally; meanwhile, a military coup is also very unlikely, considering that Venezuela's senior military leadership overall benefit from the Maduro regime.

Despite the current political crisis in Venezuela, I argue that it is extremely unlikely (98% chance) that Nicolas Maduro will cease to be president before 1 July 2018. Maduro faces a high level of disapproval from the Venezuelan people and a fairly strong opposition, although there is a low likelihood that this will result in his removal from office; there is a widespread belief among the people that they are unable to make a difference, even by voting in upcoming elections. Maduro enjoys a high level of control over the government and a growing interdependence with the military. Further, upcoming elections are likely to encourage Maduro to further consolidate his power and crack down on any source of opposition.

The escalating nature of the humanitarian and political crisis in Venezuela increases the chance that Maduro's presidency will end. The AP recently reported that Venezuela's pro-government election officials have announced that this year's election has been moved up to April (it is usually held at the end of the year). This move shuts out the opposition and adds fuel to the fire of protestors against Maduro. Venezuela's neighbors are adding to the tension. Colombia shares the humanitarian crisis, faces an influx of fleeing Venezuelans, and fears overspill of the political crisis; NPR reported today that Peru's foreign minister announced that Venezuela will not be welcome at this year's Summit of the Americas. Still, Maduro has managed to maintain his position through several months of the crisis, which is why I forecast a 50% chance that his removal from the presidency won't occur before July, even if he wins the election. Venezuela's history of clientelism complicates the issue and adds to the probability of his reelection. If he does win though (particularly if the opposition refuses to participate), the opposition may escalate, which is why I forecast his exit from the presidency at 45% between April and June.

The base rate for dictators fleeing their country is low. On a one year basis, I would put it at less than 5%. However, these are not normal days and there is growing resistance to Maduro's reign in Venezuela. Therefore, I would scale it up slightly (2x) and assign a probability of 10% for Maduro to abdicate by July 1, 2018.

It is now clear that over the last 12 months Venezuela has moved from a constitutional democracy to a one party dictatorship. It is also clear that Maduro's government (and the PSUV party) has mismanaged the country and would not be able to win any fair election (it only won a third of the seat in the December 2015 parliamentary election, and the country has continued to deteriorate in the last 18 moths, so its reasonable to assume it would win even fewer seats now). There is no question that most Venezuelans would like Maduro to go, so the question is how this could be achieved. There appears little chance that Maduro or the PSUV would allow voters the chance to remove him. The recent sham vote for a new assembly shows that no one would believe the results of an election organised by the government. So the most likely way for Maduro to go would be an overthrow. According to reports the senior officers in the army are big beneficiaries of the Maduro regime. In fact the socialist revolution appears to be degenerating into a grab for money by the senior officers and those close to Maduro before the regime collapses. This suggests that the senior officers and officials are starting to plan for taking their money and running, because they do not expect the regime to last much longer. The most likely scenarios are either officers just loose control of the troops or that junior officers launch a coup. Many of the junior officers will have families that are now against the PSUV so they are the most likely to try to get rid of Maduro. Military coups are far from unknown in Venezuela (although the last two failed) I think it almost certain that a coup will take place, the question is how long before it does and will it succeed. My guess is that a serious coup will take place in the next 6 months. And it will have a 80% chance of success.

Venezuela's security forces arrested at least 14 army officers on suspicion of "rebellion" and "treason" in the first week of protests against President Nicolas Maduro's government in early April, according to military documents seen by Reuters. The soldiers, who include colonels and captains, are being held in Ramo Verde prison in the hills outside Caracas, according to lists being circulated within the military. The lists emerged after allegations by Venezuelan opposition leaders that a purge is underway within the military to quash dissent over the handling of massive demonstrations against the socialist government since early April. The documents seen by Reuters only went up to April 8, after which the opposition and rights activists say scores more soldiers have been rounded up. The military's National Guard unit has been at the forefront of policing the protests, using tear gas, water cannons, and rubber bullets against masked youths who hurl stones, Molotov cocktails and excrement against security lines. At least 65 people have died, with victims including government and opposition supporters, bystanders and members of the security forces. Hundreds more have been injured. In public, top military officers have backed Maduro's accusation that an "armed insurrection" is being mounted by violent conspirators seeking a coup with U.S. backing. But opposition leaders say there is increasing disquiet within the military over the use of force against protesters who are demanding general elections, foreign humanitarian aid and freedom for jailed activists. https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2017-06-06/fourteen-venezuelan-army-officers-jailed-in-first-week-of-protests-documents ____________________________ COMMENTS: The situation in Venezuela in unsustainable, and not getting better while Maduro is president.
